# FQDN-scoped egress allowlist for session pods — the TIGHTENED alternative to
# networkpolicy-egress-allow.yaml.
#
# WHY: the broad example allows TCP 443 to all public IP space, which is an open
# exfiltration channel — a prompt-injected agent can POST anything it reads
# (including the session's refresh-capable Claude credential) to any public
# HTTPS host. This policy pins egress to NAMED hosts instead. See SECURITY.md
# ("Egress" section) for the threat this closes.
#
# REQUIREMENTS AND CAVEATS — read before applying:
#
#   * REQUIRES an FQDN-aware CNI. `toFQDNs` is a CiliumNetworkPolicy feature
#     (apiVersion cilium.io/v2); plain Kubernetes NetworkPolicy has no FQDN
#     support. On a non-Cilium CNI this file does nothing — use your CNI's
#     equivalent (e.g. Calico GlobalNetworkPolicy with allowed egress domains)
#     or fall back to CIDR pinning.
#
#   * REPLACES networkpolicy-egress-allow.yaml. Keep
#     networkpolicy-default-deny.yaml applied (Cilium enforces both k8s
#     NetworkPolicy and CiliumNetworkPolicy; allows are the union), apply THIS
#     file, and do NOT apply the broad-443 example — applying both re-opens
#     public 443 and defeats the point.
#
#   * RE-VERIFY THE HOST SET AGAINST A LIVE SESSION BEFORE ENFORCING. This host
#     list was compiled from Anthropic's documented Claude Code network
#     requirements (code.claude.com/docs/en/network-config, checked 2026-07-21)
#     and this repo's backend sources — it has NOT been validated against live
#     traffic from a session pod. Run a real session with this policy in
#     audit/observe mode first, e.g.:
#
#         hubble observe --namespace agent-sessions --verdict DROPPED -f
#
#     and add whatever legitimately-dropped hosts your sessions need. Agent CLI
#     releases change their endpoints over time; re-check after image bumps.
#
#   * DNS caveat: the DNS rule below permits resolution of any name so Cilium's
#     DNS proxy can populate the FQDN cache. DNS itself remains a (low-bandwidth)
#     covert channel; to narrow it, replace `matchPattern: "*"` with explicit
#     `matchName:` entries mirroring the toFQDNs list.
#
# The CLI reaches the pod via kubectl port-forward and Mutagen syncs over the
# forwarded sshd — neither is pod egress, so neither needs a rule here.
apiVersion: cilium.io/v2
kind: CiliumNetworkPolicy
metadata:
  name: egress-allow-fqdn
  namespace: agent-sessions
spec:
  endpointSelector: {}
  egress:
    # 1. DNS to cluster DNS, WITH the dns rules block — mandatory for toFQDNs:
    #    the Cilium DNS proxy learns name->IP mappings from these lookups and
    #    uses them to enforce the FQDN rules below. Adjust the selector if your
    #    cluster DNS is not kube-dns/CoreDNS in kube-system.
    - toEndpoints:
        - matchLabels:
            k8s:io.kubernetes.pod.namespace: kube-system
            k8s-app: kube-dns
      toPorts:
        - ports:
            - port: "53"
              protocol: ANY
          rules:
            dns:
              - matchPattern: "*"

    # 2. claude-pane (default backend): Claude Code endpoints, per Anthropic's
    #    documented network requirements (code.claude.com/docs/en/network-config,
    #    checked 2026-07-21):
    #      api.anthropic.com   — inference, WebFetch domain safety check,
    #                            feature flags
    #      platform.claude.com — OAuth token exchange/refresh/revocation; the
    #                            in-pod claude refreshes the materialized
    #                            .credentials.json itself, so blocking this
    #                            breaks sessions once the access token expires
    #      claude.ai           — claude.ai account authentication
    #
    #    NOT included (verify against your runner image's pinned claude version
    #    with hubble before deciding):
    #      statsig.anthropic.com, *.sentry.io — telemetry/error hosts from
    #        EARLIER documented requirement sets; absent from the current page,
    #        which instead lists the optional Datadog intake hosts
    #        (http-intake.logs.us5.datadoghq.com,
    #        browser-intake-us5-datadoghq.com). All are telemetry-only:
    #        blocked = degraded telemetry, not a broken session. Disable
    #        client-side via CLAUDE_CODE_DISABLE_NONESSENTIAL_TRAFFIC.
    #      downloads.claude.ai, raw.githubusercontent.com — auto-update checks +
    #        changelog feed; the runner image pins a sha256-verified claude
    #        binary, so in-pod auto-update is unwanted anyway.
    - toFQDNs:
        - matchName: api.anthropic.com
        - matchName: platform.claude.com
        - matchName: claude.ai
      toPorts:
        - ports:
            - port: "443"
              protocol: TCP

    # 3. codex backend (uncomment when running `sandbox codex` sessions):
    #      api.openai.com  — inference
    #      chatgpt.com + auth.openai.com — ChatGPT-OAuth token refresh
    #    (same host set the broad example's comment documents)
    # - toFQDNs:
    #     - matchName: api.openai.com
    #     - matchName: chatgpt.com
    #     - matchName: auth.openai.com
    #   toPorts:
    #     - ports:
    #         - port: "443"
    #           protocol: TCP

    # 4. opencode backend (uncomment when running `sandbox opencode` sessions).
    #    Hosts depend on which provider key the session Secret carries
    #    (runner/src/opencode.ts wires ANTHROPIC_API_KEY / OPENAI_API_KEY /
    #    OPENCODE_API_KEY into providers):
    #      opencode.ai       — opencode Zen gateway (OPENCODE_API_KEY;
    #                          API base https://opencode.ai/zen/v1)
    #      api.anthropic.com — ANTHROPIC_API_KEY provider (already allowed above)
    #      api.openai.com    — OPENAI_API_KEY provider
    # - toFQDNs:
    #     - matchName: opencode.ai
    #     - matchName: api.openai.com
    #   toPorts:
    #     - ports:
    #         - port: "443"
    #           protocol: TCP

    # 5. Workspace tooling (OPTIONAL — uncomment per need). The broad example
    #    let agents reach every public package registry; this policy does not.
    #    Add the registries your projects actually build against, e.g.:
    # - toFQDNs:
    #     - matchName: registry.npmjs.org
    #     - matchName: proxy.golang.org
    #     - matchName: sum.golang.org
    #     - matchName: pypi.org
    #     - matchName: files.pythonhosted.org
    #     - matchName: github.com
    #     - matchPattern: "*.githubusercontent.com"
    #   toPorts:
    #     - ports:
    #         - port: "443"
    #           protocol: TCP
